-- U.S. service growth rises in April: ISM survey
-- 
-- Thu May 3, 2007 10:11am EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/05/03/us-usa-economy-services-idUSN0349297920070503

 

 NEW YORK  (Reuters) - The pace of growth in the U.S. service sector rose in April, as new orders and jobs components improved, according to a report released on Thursday. 

 The Institute for Supply Management's services index rose to 56.0 in April from a four-year low of 52.4 in March. The median forecast among analysts polled Reuters was 53.0. A number above 50 indicates growth in the sector. The survey's new orders component was 55.5 in April, up from March's 53.8. The survey's prices-paid index edged up to 63.5 in April from 63.3 in March while the jobs component improved to 51.9 to from 50.8. The services sector represents about 80 percent of U.S. economic activity, including businesses such as restaurants, hotels, hair salons, banks and airlines.